snippet.textDisplay:
The modified map is fairly obvious. White says that the colonists were preparing to move when he left, so he drew a map showing where they were planning to go and build a new fort, but on returning, he found there were no colonists and no such fort had been built, so he removed it from the map.

Later he may have wanted to show where the fort was planned to be built because it was a good location for a settlement, but he didn't want the info to fall into the hands of the Spaniards or anyone else, so he drew it on in invisible ink, locatable only by those who knew it was there or who he showed.

snippet.textDisplay: 4:30 -4:42 Your wrong about Lane being paranoid. Pemisapan warned lane of 3000 Indians preparing to attack the British outpost which turned out to be true. Also Pemisapan was sending word to the Choanist Indians that the English were out to destroy them causing rivalries.Hence that is what caused strife between Lane and Pemispan. The Indians did leave the settlers with no food and would not help them and abandoned them. I can understand why because of the disease an such. But when your left to starve on an island what would you do? And if you thought Indians were gathering to attack you would you not try to stop it? Many people here seem to think it was just white folks fault without understanding the situation that happened.

snippet.textDisplay: I find it odd that the man responsible for the prosperity and survival of the colony is also the man to investigate it's demise.
